# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gcp-firestore
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] A **document-oriented database**, or **document store**, is a computer program and data storage system designed for storing, retrieving, and managing document-oriented information, also known as semi-structured data.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] Document-oriented databases are one of the main categories of NoSQL databases, and the popularity of the term "document-oriented database" has grown alongside the adoption of NoSQL itself.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] XML databases are a subclass of document-oriented databases optimized for XML documents.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] Graph databases are similar, but add another layer, the *relationship*, which allows them to link documents for rapid traversal.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] Document-oriented databases are conceptually an extension of the key–value store, another type of NoSQL database.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] In key-value stores, data is treated as opaque by the database, whereas document-oriented systems exploit the internal structure of documents to extract metadata and optimize storage and queries.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] Although in practice the distinction can be minimal due to modern tooling, document stores are designed to provide a richer programming experience with modern programming techniques.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] Document databases differ significantly from traditional relational databases (RDBs).
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] Relational databases store data in predefined tables, often requiring an object to be split across multiple tables.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] In contrast, document databases store all information for a given object in a single document, with each document potentially having a unique structure.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] This design eliminates the need for object-relational mapping when loading data into the database.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] The central concept of a document-oriented database is the notion of a *document*.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] Although implementations vary in their specific definitions, document-oriented databases generally treat documents as self-contained units that encapsulate and encode data in a standardized format.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] Common encoding formats include XML, YAML, JSON, as well as binary representations such as BSON.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] Documents in a document store are equivalent to the programming concept of an object.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] They are not required to adhere to a fixed schema, and documents within the same collection may contain different fields or structures.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] Fields may be optional, and documents of the same logical type may differ in composition.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] The two example documents share some structural elements but also contain unique fields.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] The structure, text, and other data within each document are collectively referred to as the document's content and can be accessed or modified using retrieval or editing operations.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] Unlike relational databases, in which each record contains the same fields and unused fields are left empty, document-oriented databases do not require uniform fields across documents.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] This design allows new information to be added to some documents without affecting the structure of others.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] Document databases often support the storage of additional metadata alongside the document content.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] Such metadata may relate to organizational features, security, indexing, or other implementation-specific features.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] The core operations supported by a document-oriented database for manipulating documents are similar to those in other databases.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] Although terminology is not perfectly standardized, these operations are generally recognized as Create, Read, Update, and Delete (CRUD).
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] Documents in a document-oriented database are addressed via a unique identifier.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] This identifier, often a string, URI, or path, can be used to retrieve the document from the database.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] Most document stores maintain an index on the key to optimize retrieval, and in some implementations the key is required when creating or inserting a new document.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] In addition to key-based access, document-oriented databases typically provide an API or query language that enables retrieval based on document content or associated metadata.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] For example, a query may return all documents with a specific field matching a given value.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] The available query features, indexing options, and performance characteristics vary across implementations.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] Document stores differ from key-value stores in that they exploit the internal structure and metadata of stored documents.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] In many key-value stores, values are treated as opaque or "black-box" data, meaning the database system does not interpret their internal structure.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] By contrast, document-oriented databases can classify and interpret document content.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] Document databases typically provide mechanisms for updating or editing the content or metadata of a document.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] Updates may involve replacing the entire document or modifying individual elements or fields within the document.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] These organizational structures may differ between logical and physical representations (e.g. on disk or in memory).
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] A document-oriented database can be viewed as a specialized form of key-value store, which is itself a category of NoSQL database.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] In a basic key-value store, the stored value is typically treated as opaque by the database system.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] By contrast, a document-oriented database provides APIs or a query and update language that allows queries and modifications based on the internal structure of the document.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] For users who do not require advanced query, retrieval, or update capabilities, the distinction between document-oriented databases and key-value stores may be minimal.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] Some search engine and information retrieval systems, such as Apache Solr and Elasticsearch, provide document storage and support core document operations.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] As a result, they may meet certain functional definitions of a document-oriented database, although their primary design goals differ.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] In a relational database, data is organized into predefined types represented as tables.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] Each table contains rows (records) with a fixed set of columns (fields), so all records in a table share the same structure.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] Administrators typically define indexes on selected fields to improve query performance.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] A central principle of relational database design is database normalization, in which data that might otherwise be repeated is stored in separate tables and linked using keys.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] When records in different tables are related, a foreign key is used to associate them.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] For example, an address book application may store a contact's name, image, phone numbers, mailing addresses, and email addresses.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] In a normalized relational design, separate tables might be created for contacts, phone numbers, and email addresses.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] The phone number table would include a foreign key referencing the associated contact.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] To reconstruct a complete contact record, the database retrieves related information from each table using the foreign keys and combines it into a single record.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] In contrast, a document-oriented database stores all data related to an object within a single document, and stored in the database as a single entry.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] In the address book example,the contact's name, image, and contact information may be stored together in one document.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] The document is retrieved using a unique key, and all related information is returned together, without needing to look up multiple tables.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] A key difference between the document-oriented and relational models is that the data formats are not predefined in the document case.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] In most cases, any sort of document can be stored in a database, and documents can change in type and form over time.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] For example, a new field such as COUNTRY_FLAG can be added to new documents as they are inserted without affecting existing documents.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] To aid retrieval, document-oriented systems generally allow the administrator to provide hints to the database for locating certain types of information.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] These hints work in a similar fashion to indexes in relational databases.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] Many systems also allow additional metadata outside the content of the document itself, such as tagging entries as part of an address book, which enables retrieval of related information, for instance, all the address book entries.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] This provides functionality similar to a table, but separates the concept (categories of data) from its physical implementation (tables).
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] In the traditional normalized relational model, objects in the database are represented as separate rows of data, with no inherent structure beyond what is defined in the tables.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] This can create difficulties when translating programming objects to and from their corresponding database rows, a challenge known as object-relational impedance mismatch.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] In contrast, document stores often map programming objects directly into the database, preserving much of their internal structure.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] Databases using this approach are frequently described as NoSQL systems.
[src:gcp-firestore/document-oriented-database] Most XML databases are document-oriented databases.
[src:gcp-firestore/eventual-consistency] Eventually-consistent services are often classified as providing BASE semantics (basically-available, soft-state, eventual consistency), in contrast to traditional ACID (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability).
[src:gcp-firestore/eventual-consistency] Eventual consistency faces criticism for adding complexity to distributed software applications.
[src:gcp-firestore/eventual-consistency] This complexity arises because eventual consistency provides only a liveness guarantee (ensuring reads eventually return the same value) without safety guarantees—allowing any intermediate value before convergence.
[src:gcp-firestore/eventual-consistency] Application developers find this challenging because it differs from single-threaded programming, where variables reliably return their assigned values immediately.
[src:gcp-firestore/eventual-consistency] With weak consistency guarantees, developers must carefully consider these limitations, as incorrect assumptions about consistency levels can lead to subtle bugs that only surface during network failures or high concurrency.
[src:gcp-firestore/eventual-consistency] In order to ensure replica convergence, a system must reconcile differences between multiple copies of distributed data.
[src:gcp-firestore/eventual-consistency] The most appropriate approach to reconciliation depends on the application.
[src:gcp-firestore/eventual-consistency] A widespread approach is "last writer wins".
[src:gcp-firestore/eventual-consistency] Another is to invoke a user-specified conflict handler.
[src:gcp-firestore/eventual-consistency] Timestamps and vector clocks are often used to detect concurrency between updates.
[src:gcp-firestore/eventual-consistency] Some people use "first writer wins" in situations where "last writer wins" is unacceptable.
[src:gcp-firestore/eventual-consistency] Whereas eventual consistency is only a liveness guarantee (updates will be observed eventually), **strong eventual consistency** (SEC) adds the safety guarantee that any two nodes that have received the same (unordered) set of updates will be in the same state.
[src:gcp-firestore/eventual-consistency] A common approach to ensure SEC is conflict-free replicated data types.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] Its name continues as a set of backend cloud computing services and application development platforms provided by Google.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] It hosts databases, services, authentication, and integration for a variety of applications, including Android, iOS, JavaScript, Node.js, Java, Unity, PHP, and C++.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] Firebase evolved from Envolve, a prior startup founded by James Tamplin and Andrew Lee in 2011.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] Envolve provided developers an API that enables the integration of online chat functionality into their websites.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] After releasing the chat service, Tamplin and Lee found out that it was being used to pass application data that were not chat messages.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] Developers were using Envolve to sync application data such as game state in real time across their users.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] Tamplin and Lee decided to separate the chat system and the real-time architecture that powered it.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] They founded Firebase as a separate company in 2011 and it launched to the public in April 2012.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] Firebase's first product was the Firebase Realtime Database, an API that synchronizes application data across iOS, Android, and Web devices, and stores it on Firebase's cloud.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] The product assists software developers in building real-time, collaborative applications.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] In May 2012, a month after the beta launch, Firebase raised $1.1 million in seed funding from venture capitalists Flybridge Capital Partners, Greylock Partners, Founder Collective, and New Enterprise Associates.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] In June 2013, the company further raised $5.6 million in Series A funding from Union Square Ventures and Flybridge Capital Partners.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] In 2014, Firebase launched two products: Firebase Hosting and Firebase Authentication.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] This positioned the company as a mobile backend as a service.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] In October 2014, Firebase was acquired by Google.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] A year later, in October 2015, Google acquired Divshot, an HTML5 web-hosting platform, to merge it with the Firebase team.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] In May 2016, at Google I/O, the company's annual developer conference, Google introduced Firebase Analytics and announced that it was expanding its services to become a unified backend-as-a-service (BaaS) platform for mobile developers.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] Firebase now integrates with various other Google services, including Google Cloud Platform, AdMob, and Google Ads to offer broader products and scale for developers.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] Google Cloud Messaging, the Google service to send push notifications to Android devices, was superseded by a Firebase product, Firebase Cloud Messaging, which added the functionality to deliver push notifications to Android, iOS and web devices.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] In July 2016 Google announced that it was acquiring the mobile developer platform LaunchKit, which specialized in app developer marketing, and would be folding it into the Firebase Growth Tools team.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] In January 2017, Google acquired Fabric and Crashlytics from Twitter to add those services to Firebase.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] In October 2017 Google launched Cloud Firestore, a real-time document database as the successor product to the original Firebase Realtime Database.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] Firebase software has been claimed to be used by Google to track users without their knowledge.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] On July 14, 2020, a lawsuit was filed accusing Google of violating federal wire tap law and California privacy law.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] It stated that through Firebase, Google collected and stored user data, logging what the user was looking at in many types of apps, despite the user following Google's own instructions to turn off the web and app activity collected by the company.
[src:gcp-firestore/firebase] The lawsuit was dismissed in January 2022, with Chief US District Judge Richard Seeborg ruling that a promise to avoid collecting user data did not amount to a contract.
[src:gcp-firestore/mobile-backend-as-a-service] Web and mobile apps require a similar set of features on the backend, including notification service, integration with social networks, and cloud storage.
[src:gcp-firestore/mobile-backend-as-a-service] Each of these services has its own API that must be individually incorporated into an app, a process that can be time-consuming and complicated for app developers.
[src:gcp-firestore/mobile-backend-as-a-service] BaaS providers form a bridge between the frontend of an application and various cloud-based backends via a unified API and SDK.
[src:gcp-firestore/mobile-backend-as-a-service] Providing a consistent way to manage backend data means that developers do not need to redevelop their own backend for each of the services that their apps need to access, potentially saving both time and money.
[src:gcp-firestore/mobile-backend-as-a-service] BaaS providers offer different set of features and backend tools.
[src:gcp-firestore/mobile-backend-as-a-service] BaaS providers also come in different types, suiting developers of different needs.
[src:gcp-firestore/mobile-backend-as-a-service] Most BaaS providers host backend platforms on their cloud servers.
[src:gcp-firestore/mobile-backend-as-a-service] They also manage the infrastructure, security, and scalability of the platforms.
[src:gcp-firestore/mobile-backend-as-a-service] Developers can access the backend services via a web interface or the provided APIs.
[src:gcp-firestore/mobile-backend-as-a-service] Some examples of cloud-based BaaS include Firebase (hosted on Google Cloud Platform), AWS Amplify (hosted on Amazon Web Services), and Microsoft Azure Mobile Apps (hosted on Microsoft Azure).
[src:gcp-firestore/mobile-backend-as-a-service] Self-hosted BaaS allow developers to host backend on their own servers, providing more flexibility and potential to customization compared to cloud-based BaaS, which often is more difficult to migrate from.
[src:gcp-firestore/mobile-backend-as-a-service] However, developers are also in charge of managing the infrastructure, security, and scalability of their servers.
[src:gcp-firestore/mobile-backend-as-a-service] Mobile backend as a service (MBaaS) is a type of BaaS specifically for applications deployed in mobile systems.
[src:gcp-firestore/mobile-backend-as-a-service] While some references use MBaaS interchangeably for BaaS, BaaS can have a wider variety of support such as for web apps and desktop apps.
[src:gcp-firestore/mobile-backend-as-a-service] BaaS providers generate revenue from their services in various ways, often using a freemium model.
[src:gcp-firestore/mobile-backend-as-a-service] Under this model, a client receives a certain number of free active users or API calls per month, and pays a fee for each user or call over this limit.
[src:gcp-firestore/mobile-backend-as-a-service] Alternatively, clients can pay a set fee for a package which allows for a greater number of calls or active users per month.
[src:gcp-firestore/mobile-backend-as-a-service] There are also flat fee plans that make the pricing more predictable.
[src:gcp-firestore/mobile-backend-as-a-service] Some of the providers offer the unlimited API calls inside their free plan offerings.
[src:gcp-firestore/mobile-backend-as-a-service] Another business model that has been used by a lot of BaaS providers is PAYG (pay as you go), which has a flexible cost based on developers' usage of database, storage, bandwidth, function calls, user numbers etc.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] NoSQL databases are popular in big data and real-time web applications due to their simple design, ability to scale across clusters of machines (called horizontal scaling), and precise control over data availability.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] These structures can speed up certain tasks and are often considered more adaptable than fixed database tables.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] However, many NoSQL systems prioritize speed and availability over strict consistency (per the CAP theorem), using eventual consistency—where updates reach all nodes eventually, typically within milliseconds, but may cause brief delays in accessing the latest data, known as stale reads.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] While most lack full ACID transaction support, some, like MongoDB, include it as a key feature.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] Barriers to wider NoSQL adoption include their use of low-level query languages instead of SQL, inability to perform ad hoc joins across tables, lack of standardized interfaces, and significant investments already made in relational databases.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] Some NoSQL systems risk losing data through lost writes or other forms, though features like write-ahead logging—a method to record changes before they’re applied—can help prevent this.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] Limitations within the interface environment are overcome using semantic virtualization protocols, such that NoSQL services are accessible to most operating systems.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] The term *NoSQL* was used by Carlo Strozzi in 1998 to name his lightweight Strozzi NoSQL open-source relational database that did not expose the standard Structured Query Language (SQL) interface, but was still relational.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] His NoSQL RDBMS is distinct from the around-2009 general concept of NoSQL databases.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] Strozzi suggests that, because the current NoSQL movement "departs from the relational model altogether, it should therefore have been called more appropriately 'NoREL'", referring to "not relational".
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] Johan Oskarsson, then a developer at Last.fm, reintroduced the term *NoSQL* in early 2009 when he organized an event to discuss "open-source distributed, non-relational databases".
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] The name attempted to label the emergence of an increasing number of non-relational, distributed data stores, including open source clones of Google's Bigtable/MapReduce and Amazon's DynamoDB.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] There are various ways to classify NoSQL databases, with different categories and subcategories, some of which overlap.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] Key–value (KV) stores use the associative array (also called a map or dictionary) as their fundamental data model.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] In this model, data is represented as a collection of key–value pairs, such that each possible key appears at most once in the collection.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] The key–value model is one of the simplest non-trivial data models, and richer data models are often implemented as an extension of it.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] The key–value model can be extended to a discretely ordered model that maintains keys in lexicographic order.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] This extension is computationally powerful, in that it can efficiently retrieve selective key *ranges*.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] Key–value stores can use consistency models ranging from eventual consistency to serializability.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] Some databases support ordering of keys.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] There are various hardware implementations, and some users store data in memory (RAM), while others on solid-state drives (SSD) or rotating disks (aka hard disk drive (HDD)).
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] The central concept of a document store is that of a "document".
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] While the details of this definition differ among document-oriented databases, they all assume that documents encapsulate and encode data (or information) in some standard formats or encodings.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] Encodings in use include XML, YAML, and JSON and binary forms like BSON.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] Documents are addressed in the database via a unique *key* that represents that document.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] Another defining characteristic of a document-oriented database is an API or query language to retrieve documents based on their contents.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] Compared to relational databases, collections could be considered analogous to tables and documents analogous to records.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] But they are different – every record in a table has the same sequence of fields, while documents in a collection may have fields that are completely different.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] Graph databases are designed for data whose relations are well represented as a graph consisting of elements connected by a finite number of relations.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] Examples of data include social relations, public transport links, road maps, network topologies, etc.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] The performance of NoSQL databases is usually evaluated using the metric of throughput, which is measured as operations per second.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] Performance evaluation must pay attention to the right benchmarks such as production configurations, parameters of the databases, anticipated data volume, and concurrent user workloads.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] Performance and scalability comparisons are most commonly done using the YCSB benchmark.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] Since most NoSQL databases lack ability for joins in queries, the database schema generally needs to be designed differently.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] There are three main techniques for handling relational data in a NoSQL database.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] Instead of retrieving all the data with one query, it is common to do several queries to get the desired data.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] NoSQL queries are often faster than traditional SQL queries, so the cost of additional queries may be acceptable.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] If an excessive number of queries would be necessary, one of the other two approaches is more appropriate.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] Instead of only storing foreign keys, it is common to store actual foreign values along with the model's data.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] For example, each blog comment might include the username in addition to a user id, thus providing easy access to the username without requiring another lookup.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] When a username changes, however, this will now need to be changed in many places in the database.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] Thus this approach works better when reads are much more common than writes.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] With document databases like MongoDB it is common to put more data in a smaller number of collections.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] For example, in a blogging application, one might choose to store comments within the blog post document, so that with a single retrieval one gets all the comments.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] Thus in this approach a single document contains all the data needed for a specific task.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] A database is marked as supporting ACID properties (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) or join operations if the documentation for the database makes that claim.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] However, this doesn't necessarily mean that the capability is fully supported in a manner similar to most SQL databases.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] MongoDB did not support joining from a sharded collection until version 5.1.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] OrientDB can resolve 1:1 joins using links by storing direct links to foreign records.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] Different NoSQL databases, such as DynamoDB, MongoDB, Cassandra, Couchbase, HBase, and Redis, exhibit varying behaviors when querying non-indexed fields.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] Many perform full-table or collection scans for such queries, applying filtering operations after retrieving data.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] However, modern NoSQL databases often incorporate advanced features to optimize query performance.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] For example, MongoDB supports compound indexes and query-optimization strategies, Cassandra offers secondary indexes and materialized views, and Redis employs custom indexing mechanisms tailored to specific use cases.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] Systems like Elasticsearch use inverted indexes for efficient text-based searches, but they can still require full scans for non-indexed fields.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] This behavior reflects the design focus of many NoSQL systems on scalability and efficient key-based operations rather than optimized querying for arbitrary fields.
[src:gcp-firestore/nosql] Consequently, while these databases excel at basic CRUD operations and key-based lookups, their suitability for complex queries involving joins or non-indexed filtering varies depending on the database type—document, key–value, wide-column, or graph—and the specific implementation.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] The second meaning of the term “real-time database” adheres to a stricter definition of real-time consistent with Real-time computing.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] While the performance metric for most database systems is throughput or transactions-per-second, the performance metric of a hard real-time database system is the ratio of committed-to-aborted transactions.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] This ratio indicates how effective the transaction scheduling policy is, with the ultimate goal of meeting deadlines 100% of the time.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Hard real-time databases, through enforcement of deadlines, may not allow transactions to be late (overrun the deadline).
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Real-time databases are traditional databases that use an extension to give the additional power to yield reliable responses.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] They use timing constraints that represent a certain range of values for which the data are valid.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] A conventional database cannot work under these circumstances because the inconsistencies between the real world objects and the data that represents them are too severe for simple modifications.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] An effective system needs to be able to handle time-sensitive queries, return only temporally valid data, and support priority scheduling.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] To enter the data in the records, often a sensor or an input device monitors the state of the physical system and updates the database with new information to reflect the physical system more accurately.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] When designing a real-time database system, one should consider how to represent valid time, how facts are associated with real-time system.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Also, consider how to represent attribute values in the database so that process transactions and data consistency have no violations.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] When designing a system, it is important to consider what the system should do when deadlines are not met.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] For example, an air-traffic control system constantly monitors hundreds of aircraft and makes decisions about incoming flight paths and determines the order in which aircraft should land based on data such as fuel, altitude, and speed.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] If any of this information is late, the result could be devastating.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] To address issues of obsolete data, the timestamp can support transactions by providing clear time references.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Although the real-time database system may seem like a simple system, problems arise during overload when two or more database transactions require access to the same portion of the database.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] A transaction is usually the result of an execution of a program that accesses or changes the contents of a database.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] A transaction is different from a stream because a stream only allows read-only operations, and transactions can do both read and write operations.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] This means in a stream, multiple users can read from the same piece of data, but they cannot both modify it.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] A database must let only one transaction operate at a time to preserve data consistency.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] For example, if two students demand to take the remaining spot for a section of a class and they hit submit at the same time, only one student should be able to register for it.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Real-time databases can process these requests utilizing scheduling algorithms for concurrency control, prioritizing both students’ requests in some way.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Throughout this article, we assume that the system has a single processor, a disk based database, and a main memory pool.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] In real-time databases, deadlines are formed and different kinds of systems respond to data that does not meet its deadline in different ways.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] In a real-time system, each transaction uses a timestamp to schedule the transactions.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] A priority mapper unit assigns a level of importance to each transaction upon its arrival in the database system that is dependent on how the system views times and other priorities.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] The timestamp method relies on the arrival time in the system.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Researchers indicate that for most studies, transactions are sporadic with unpredictable arrival times.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] For example, the system gives an earlier request deadline to a higher priority and a later deadline to a lower priority.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Below is a comparison of different scheduling algorithms.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] — The value of a transaction is not important.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] An example is a group of people calling to order a product.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Some transactions should get to CPU based on criticalness, not fairness.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] This is an example of least slack that can wait the least amount of time.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] If the telephone switchboards were overloaded, people who call 911 should get priority.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] — Gives equal weight to deadline and values based on scheduling.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] An example is registering for classes where the student selects a block of classes that he wishes to take and presses submit.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] In this scenario, higher priorities often take up precedence.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] A school registration system probably uses this technique when the server receives two registration transactions.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] If one student had 22 credits and the other had 100 credits, the person with 100 credits would take priority (Value based scheduling).
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] A system that correctly perceives the serialization and timing constraints associated with transactions with soft or firm deadlines, takes advantage of absolute consistency.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Another way of making sure that data is absolute is using relative constraints.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Relative constraints ensure transactions enter into the system at the same time as the rest of the group that the data transaction is associated with.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Using the mechanisms of absolute and relative constraints greatly ensures the accuracy of data.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] An additional way of dealing with conflict resolution in a real-time database system besides deadlines is a wait policy method.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] This process helps ensure the latest information in time critical systems.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] The policy avoids conflict by asking all non-requesting blocks to wait until the most essential block of data is processed.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] While studies in labs have found that data-deadline based policies do not improve performance significantly, the forced wait policy can improve performance by 50 percent.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] The forced wait policy may involve waiting for higher priority transactions to process in order to prevent deadlock.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Another example of when data can be delayed is when a block of data is about to expire.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] The forced wait policy delays processing until the data is updated using new input data.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] The latter method helps increase the accuracy of the system and can cut down on the number of necessary processes that are aborted.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Generally, relying on wait policies is not optimal.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] It is necessary to discuss the formation of deadlines.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Deadlines are the constraints for soon-to-be replaced data accessed by the transaction.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Deadlines can be either observant or predictive.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] In an observant deadline system, all unfinished transactions are examined and the processor determines whether any had met its deadline.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Problems arise in this method because of variations caused by seek time variations, buffer management and page faults.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] A more stable way of organizing deadlines is the predictive method.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] It builds a candidate schedule and determines if a transaction would miss its deadline under the schedule.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] The type of response to a missed deadline depends on whether the deadline is hard, soft, or firm.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Hard deadlines require that each data packet reach its destination before the packet has expired and if not, the process could be lost, causing a possible problem.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Problems like these are not very common because omnipotence of the system is required before assigning deadlines to determine worst case.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] This is very hard to do and if something unexpected happens to the system such as a minute hardware glitch, it could throw the data off.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] For soft or firm deadlines, missing a deadline can lead to a degraded performance but not a catastrophe.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] A soft deadline meets as many deadlines as possible.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] However, no guarantee exists that the system can meet all deadlines.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Should a transaction miss its deadline, the system has more flexibility and the transaction may increase in importance.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] If not meeting deadlines creates problems, a hard deadline is best.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] It is periodic, meaning that it enters the database on a regular rhythmic pattern.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] An example is data gathered by a sensor.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] These are often used in life critical systems.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Firm deadlines appear to be similar to hard deadlines yet they differ from hard deadlines because firm deadlines measure how important it is to complete the transaction at some point after the transaction arrives.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Sometimes completing a transaction after its deadline has expired may be harmful or not helpful, and both the firm and hard deadlines consider this.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] An example of a firm deadline is an autopilot system.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] If meeting time constrains is desirable but missing deadlines do not cause serious damage, a soft deadline may be best.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] It operates on an aperiodic or irregular schedule.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] In fact, the arrival of each time for each task is unknown.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] An example is an operator switchboard for a telephone.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Hard deadline processes abort transactions that have passed the deadline, improving the system by cleaning out clutter that needs to be processed.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Processes can clear out not only the transactions with expired deadlines but also transactions with the longest deadlines, assuming that once they reach the processor they would be obsolete.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] This means other transactions should be of higher priority.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] In addition, a system can remove the least critical transactions.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] This error is caused by the checker, a mechanism that checks the condition of the rules, and the rule that occurred before it.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] The goal of scheduling periods and deadlines is to update transactions guaranteed to complete before their deadline in such a way that the workload is minimal.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] With large real-time databases, buffering functions can help improve performance tremendously.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] A buffer is part of the database that is stored in main memory to reduce transaction response time.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] In order to reduce disk input and output transactions, a certain number of buffers should be allocated.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Sometimes multiversions are stored in buffers when the data block the transaction needs is currently in use.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Later, the database has the data appended to it.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Different strategies allocate buffers and must balance between taking an excessive amount of memory and having everything in one buffer that it has to search for.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] The goal is to eliminate search time and distribute the resources between buffer frames in order to access data quickly.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] A buffer manager is capable of allocating more memory, if necessary, to improve response time.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] The buffer manager can even determine whether a transaction that it has should advance.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Buffering can improve speed in real-time systems.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Traditional databases are persistent but are incapable of dealing with dynamic data that constantly changes.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Real-time databases may be modified to improve accuracy and efficiency and to avoid conflict, by providing deadlines and wait periods to insure temporal consistency.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Real-time database systems offer a way of monitoring a physical system and representing it in data streams to a database.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] A data stream, like memory, fades over time.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] In order to guarantee that the freshest and most accurate information is recorded there are a number of ways of checking transactions to make sure they are executed in the proper order.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] An online auction house provides an example of a rapidly changing database.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Now database systems are faster than they were in the past.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] In the future, we can look forward to even faster database systems.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Although we have faster systems now, an effort to reduce misses and tardy times will still be beneficial.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] The ability to process results in a timely and predictable manner will always be more important than fast processing.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Fast processing that is misapplied is not helpful for real-time database systems.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Transactions that run faster still sometimes block in such a way that they have to be aborted and restarted.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] In fact, faster processing hurts some real-time applications because increased speed brings more complexity and more of a chance for problems caused by a variance of speed.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Faster processing makes it harder to determine which deadlines have been met successfully.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] With future database systems running even faster than ever, there is a need to do more studies so we can continue to have efficient systems.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] The amount of research studying real-time database systems will increase because of commercial applications such as web based auction houses like eBay.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] More developing countries are expanding their phone systems, and the number of people with cell phones in the United States as well as other places in the world continues to grow.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Also likely to spur real-time research is the exponentially increasing speed of the microprocessor.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] This also enables new technologies such as web-video conferencing and instant messenger conversations in sound and high-resolution video, which are reliant on real-time database systems.
[src:gcp-firestore/real-time-database] Studies of temporal consistency result in new protocols and timing constraints with the goal of handling real-time transactions more effectively.
